<center><span style="font-size: 22px; font-family: Asterisma;">'''My Findings No. 7'''</span></center>
<br><br>
<div style="margin: 1em;">
Found in 2007, the diary was the first record of '''Level 2'''. Written in 1762 by an unidentified explorer, Arthur T., whose surname is unidentifiable due to a lacuna, was found slipped in between two pipelines.
<center>'''''AN ODYSSEY'''''</center>
<br>
To pristine, white rocks! I wondered what Zechariah would have said to me. Would he have called me Ishmael? Perhaps the pettifogging was too much for when the crumbling marble that surrounded the Ingleton-esque caves spoke to me like I was Belshazzar. The future was telling me to go thither. Something's been flowing through me during these times of hardship;—even I reminisced about my matrimony back home.
[[File:Hallway1700s.png|link=|right|300px]]
And how have I not mentioned the woven cannon barrels that line up the walls? Spheroids of bees inside and clouds not contrasted by the blues. The cramped and unreasonably elongated attic rained from a not-so-great height and the stench of rotten cattle from a thousand brittle skeletons underground of Paris. Persons in their towering periwigs and their shoulder caps with peacock feathers foliaged in the fitted bodices like stars on the sky.

Thenceforth I end this for today and you will be expecting a second handful of paper in one fortnight. As dull as the advances have made my home—as they say—''"L'habit ne fait pas le moine."'' The folks, the wanderers, as they say on the carvings on the walls, and I've sworn I could catch up to them, catch on their ways. ''Have I spelled it out correctly?
<br><br>
[[File:Johnlennon.png|center|100px|link=]]
<br><br>
